    "title": "Checking IV Admixtures",
    "description": "The process of properly verifying prepared syringes in the IV room",
    "category": "iv-room",
    "slug": "checking-iv-admixtures",
    "content": "\n## Priority of checking based on bin color \n- Yellow = STAT\n- Green = Narcotic\n- Blue = First dose\n- Clear = Cartfill\n\n## IV product label and production label matches \n- Same patient, medication, dose, etc. \n\n## Bag and base fluid \n- If a pre-made bag: correct bag/ fluid type and volume \n- If a pumped bag: check pictures in MedKeeper taken by tech of volume and fluid type \n- If an empty bag: check to see if a certain type of bag is needed (e.g. non DEHP) \n\n## Medication used matches production label \n\nMedication name, concentration, form (e.g. liposomal), vial size \n- Be aware of products with multiple concentrations: dexamethasone, methylprednisolone, gentamicin, phenobarbital, dilutions, etc. \n\nCheck expiration date \n- Manufacturer expiration date not exceeded \n- Single dose vials- 6 hours, THROW AWAY \n- Multi dose vials- 28 days, MUST BE DATED! \n    - Exceptions: Octreotide 14days, Bactrim 48hrs \n- Batched product beyond use date not exceeded \n\nIf reconstituted: \n- Refer to the “Non-Chemo Vial Reconstitution and Stability” document found here in Appendix B \n- If not on the reconstitution chart, follow the package insert \n- Reconstituted vial must be stickered with reconstitution information & expiration date \n- Initial the pharmacist checked line on the sticker if just reconstituted \n\n## Volume of medication used (pull back method)\n- Do calculations make sense?\n- Empty syringe pulled back to the volume indication on production label \n- Be aware of common concentration limitations: \n    - Acyclovir must not exceed 7mg/ml \n    - Bactrim is usually 5ml drug per 75ml fluid \n\n## Review special notes on production label \n- Special Tubing required – “Non-Chemo Tubing Reference Sheet” found in PolicyStat \n- Additional information on product preparation. E.g. Peculiar Preparation instructions \n\n## Initial production label and final product \n- Place production label in storage bin on checking counter (Stored for 14 days and shredded) \n\n## Place in plastic bag (if applicable) \n- Ensue If protect from light required, it is placed in a green or amber bag \n\n## Attach delivery slip (if applicable) \n\n## Disposal of products used \n- Garbage = Plastic products, used IV fluid bags \n- Blue/green bin = Glass vials (nonhazardous) \n- Black bin = hazardous waste \n\n## Place checked product in designation area for delivery \n- Tubed, Hand delivered, Refrigerator \n- Communicate with techs if product is STAT or needs delivered ASAP",
